04854nam a2200565Ia 9780226823133DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226823133  a(DE-B1597)633883  a(OCoLC)1357017403  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a618.20094qOCoLC1 aWhiteley, Rebecca, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBirth Figures :bEarly Modern Prints and the Pregnant Body /cRebecca Whiteley. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b6 color plates, 55 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tA Note on Terminology -- tIntroduction. Picturing Pregnancy -- tPart I. Early Printed Birth Figures (1540– 1672) -- tOne. Using Images in Midwifery Practice -- tTwo. Pluralistic Images and the Early Modern Body -- tPart II. Birth Figures as Agents of Change (1672– 1751) -- tThree. Visual Experiments -- tFour . Visualizing Touch and Defining a Professional Persona -- tPart III. The Birth Figure Persists (1751– 1774) -- tFive. Challenging the Hunterian Hegemony -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first full study of “birth figures” and their place in early modern knowledge-making. Birth figures are printed images of the pregnant womb, always shown in series, that depict the variety of ways in which a fetus can present for birth. Historian Rebecca Whiteley coined the term and here offers the first systematic analysis of the images’ creation, use, and impact. Whiteley reveals their origins in ancient medicine and explores their inclusion in many medieval gynecological manuscripts, focusing on their explosion in printed midwifery and surgical books in Western Europe from the mid-sixteenth to the mid-eighteenth century. During this period, birth figures formed a key part of the visual culture of medicine and midwifery and were widely produced. They reflected and shaped how the pregnant body was known and treated. And by providing crucial bodily knowledge to midwives and surgeons, birth figures were also deeply entangled with wider cultural preoccupations with generation and creativity, female power and agency, knowledge and its dissemination, and even the condition of the human in the universe. Birth Figures studies how different kinds of people understood childbirth and engaged with midwifery manuals, from learned physicians to midwives to illiterate listeners. Rich and detailed, this vital history reveals the importance of birth figures in how midwifery was practiced and in how people, both medical professionals and lay readers, envisioned and understood the mysterious state of pregnancy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMedical illustration-History. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  abody history, book history, illustrations, childbirth, epistemic images, history of medicine, midwifery, pregnancy, prints, visual culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2023z9783111318103oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2023 Englishz978311131903208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076650940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226823133423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226823133/original